"Hori H., Takano Y., Koike K., Takeuchi K., Einaga H.","Decomposition of environmentally persistent trifluoroacetic acid to fluoride ions by a homogeneous photocatalyst in water",2003,"Environmental Science and Technology","37","2",,"418","422",,,10.1021/es025783y,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037439039&partnerID=40&md5=f42b8daebd615da99dac3b741906a7f3","National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan","Hori, H., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan; Takano, Y., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan; Koike, K., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan; Takeuchi, K., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan; Einaga, H., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), AIST Tsukuba West, 16-1 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8569, Japan","Decomposition of trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) was achieved with a tungstic heteropolyacid photocatalyst H3PW12O40· 6H2O in order to develop a technique for measures against TFA stationary sources. This is the first example of C-F bond cleavage in an environmentally harmful perfluoromethyl-group-containing compound using a homogeneous photocatalyst. The catalytic reaction proceeds in water at room temperature under UV-visible light irradiation in the presence of oxygen. The system produces only F- ions and CO2; the (mole of formed F-)/(mole of decomposed TFA) and (mole of formed CO2)/(mole of decomposed TFA) ratios were 2.91 and 2.09, respectively. GC/MS measurements showed no trace of other species such as environmentally undesirable CF4, which is the most stable perfluorocarbon and has a very high global warming potential. When the (initial TFA)/(initial catalyst) molar ratio was 20:1, the turnover number of TFA decomposition reached 5.58 by 72 h of irradiation, accompanying with no catalyst degradation. The catalytic reaction mechanism can be explained by a redox reaction between the catalyst and TFA, involving a photo-Kolbe process.",,"Photocatalysts; Catalysts; Chemical bonds; Decomposition; Degradation; Global warming; Irradiation; Oxygen; Redox reactions; Ultraviolet radiation; Acetic acid; trifluoroacetic acid; photodegradation; article; catalysis; decomposition; gas chromatography; greenhouse effect; irradiation; mass spectrometry; molecular mechanics; oxidation reduction reaction; photochemistry; phototherapy; room temperature; water management; Catalysis; Fluorides; Photochemistry; Temperature; Trifluoroacetic Acid; Water Pollutants, Chemical; Water Purification",,"trifluoroacetic acid, 14477-72-6, 2923-18-4, 76-05-1; Fluorides; Trifluoroacetic Acid, 76-05-1; Water Pollutants, Chemical",,,,"(2001) Material Safety Data Sheet, , Aldrich Chemical Co. Inc., Milwaukee; Von Sydow, L.M., Grimvall, A.B., Borén, H.B., Laniewski, K., Nielsen, A.T., (2000) Environ. Sci. Technol., 34, pp. 3115-3118; Scott, B.F., Mactavish, D., Spencer, C., Strachan, W.M.J., Muir, D.C.G., (2000) Environ. Sci. Technol., 34, pp. 4266-4272; Berg, M., Müller, S.R., Mühlemann, J., Wiedmer, A., Schwarzenbach, R.P., (2000) Environ. Sci. Technol., 34, pp. 2675-2683; Jordan, A., Frank, H., (1999) Environ. Sci. Technol., 33, pp. 522-527; Wallington, T.J., Hurley, M.D., Fracheboud, J.M., Orlando, J.J., Tyndall, G.S., Sehested, J., Møgelberg, T.E., Nielsen, O.J., (1996) J. Phys. Chem., 100, pp. 18116-18122; Ellis, D.A., Mabury, S.A., Martin, J.W., Muir, D.C.G., (2001) Nature, 412, pp. 321-324; Kim, B.R., Suidan, M.T., Wallington, T.J., Du, X., (2000) Environ. Eng. Sci., 17, pp. 337-342; Martin, J.W., Fra